IMPLEMENTATION AND COMPARATIVE ANALYSIS OF MACHINE LEARNING MODELS¶

INTRODUCTION¶

In this notebook, we aim to implement and compare the performance of various machine learning models on a given dataset. The models under consideration include:¶

  • Random Forest Classifier
  • K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)
  • Decision Tree Classifier
  • Logistic Regression
  • Artificial Neural Network (ANN)

Each model will be evaluated based on its accuracy, confusion matrix, and classification report. The purpose of this comparative analysis is to identify the most effective model for the dataset and understand the strengths and weaknesses of each approach. Through this comprehensive evaluation, we aim to provide insights into the performance of different machine learning algorithms, thereby aiding in the selection of the most appropriate model for predictive tasks in similar contexts.¶

In [13]:
# Create subplots with one row and two columns, and set the figure size
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 7), constrained_layout=True)

# Define a function for plotting a histogram with customized parameters
def plot_hist(data, bins=20, title='', xlabel='', ax=None):
    # Use the provided axes or create new ones if not provided
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    
    # Plot the histogram
    ax.hist(data, bins=bins, color='#86bf91', edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)

    # Set labels and title
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=14, weight='bold')
    ax.set_xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)

    # Add grid for better readability
    ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# Plot the histogram for BMI
plot_hist(df.bmi,
          title='Distribution of BMI',
          xlabel='Level of BMI',
          ax=axes[0])

# Plot the histogram for Age with custom bin count
plot_hist(df.age,
          bins=30,
          title='Distribution of Age',
          xlabel='Age',
          ax=axes[1])

# Show the plot
plt.show()

Examining the confusion matrix, a notable pattern emerges: the highest similarity is observed between predictions for the "Stroke" (target feature) and the "Age" feature. This suggests that the model relies heavily on age-related information for stroke predictions, while BMI appears to have less impact on the predictive outcomes¶

Balancing the dataset¶

In [30]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# Separate features and target variable
X = df_encoded.drop(columns=['stroke'])
y = df_encoded['stroke']

# Apply SMOTE to balance the 'stroke' column
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X, y)

# Convert the resampled dataset back to DataFrame
X_resampled_df = pd.DataFrame(X_resampled, columns=X.columns)
y_resampled_df = pd.DataFrame(y_resampled, columns=['stroke'])

# Combine the features and target variable
resampled_data = pd.concat([X_resampled_df, y_resampled_df], axis=1)

# Manually balance 'hypertension' and 'heart_disease' columns
for column in ['hypertension', 'heart_disease']:
    max_samples = resampled_data[column].value_counts().max()
    balanced_data = pd.DataFrame()
    for class_value in resampled_data[column].unique():
        class_data = resampled_data[resampled_data[column] == class_value]
        balanced_class_data = class_data.sample(max_samples, replace=True, random_state=42)
        balanced_data = pd.concat([balanced_data, balanced_class_data], axis=0)
    resampled_data = balanced_data

# Shuffle the dataset to mix the classes
resampled_data = resampled_data.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Save the balanced dataset to a CSV file
balanced_file_path = 'healthcare-dataset-stroke-data-balanced.csv'
resampled_data.to_csv(balanced_file_path, index=False)

print(f"Balanced dataset saved to {balanced_file_path}")

Balanced dataset saved to healthcare-dataset-stroke-data-balanced.csv

The Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) method is employed to select the most significant features for model training. RFE is a model-based method that recursively removes the least important features based on the estimator model's weights. In this case, logistic regression is used as the estimator model. Which gives top 13 features that will be later used for model training. Selected features are 'age', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'gender', 'ever_married','Residence_type', 'work_type_Never_worked', 'work_type_Private','work_type_Self-employed', 'work_type_children','smoking_status_formerly smoked', 'smoking_status_never smoked','smoking_status_smokes'.¶

features = ['age', 'hypertension', 'heart_disease', 'gender', 'ever_married','Residence_type', 'avg_glucose_level','work_type_Never_worked',
            'work_type_Private', 'work_type_Self-employed', 'work_type_children', 'smoking_status_formerly smoked', 'smoking_status_never smoked',
            'smoking_status_smokes']

# Extract the selected features (X) and the target variable (Y) from the DataFrame
X = df[features]
Y = df['stroke']

# Convert categorical variables to numerical using LabelEncoder
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()
for column in X.columns:
    if X[column].dtype == 'object':
        X[column] = label_encoder.fit_transform(X[column])

# Perform train-test split on the feature set (X) and target variable (Y)
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y,random_state=65, test_size=0.2)

Build the ANN model¶

In [49]:
from tensorflow import keras

# Define a sequential model
model = keras.Sequential([
    # Add a dense (fully connected) layer with 30 neurons, input shape is (14,)
    # The input shape should match the number of features in your dataset
    keras.layers.Dense(30, input_shape=(14,), activation='relu'),  # First hidden layer with ReLU activation

    # Add a dense layer with 25 neurons and ReLU activation function
    keras.layers.Dense(25, activation='relu'),  # Second hidden layer with ReLU activation

    # Add a dense layer with 20 neurons and ReLU activation function
    keras.layers.Dense(20, activation='relu'),  # Third hidden layer with ReLU activation

    # Add a dense layer with 15 neurons and ReLU activation function
    keras.layers.Dense(15, activation='relu'),  # Fourth hidden layer with ReLU activation

    # Add a dense layer with 1 neuron and sigmoid activation function
    # This is the output layer, sigmoid is used for binary classification
    keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')  # Output layer with Sigmoid activation
])

# Compile the model with specified optimizer, loss function, and metrics
model.compile(optimizer='adam',  # Adam optimizer, an efficient version of gradient descent
              loss='binary_crossentropy',  # Binary crossentropy loss for binary classification
              metrics=['accuracy'])  # Track accuracy during training

# Print the summary of the model architecture
model.summary()  # Print the model summary to show the architecture

# Calculate the accuracy of the model by comparing predicted and actual values
accuracy_ann = accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred_ann)

# Generate the confusion matrix to evaluate the performance of the classification model

In summary, based on the accuracy metrics:¶

  • #### Random Forest Classifier achieved the highest accuracy of 99.44%, indicating it is the most effective model for the given dataset.
  • #### Decision Tree Classifier closely followed with an accuracy of 99.22%, also demonstrating high predictive performance.
  • #### Artificial Neural Network (ANN) performed exceptionally well with an accuracy of 98.54%, making it a strong contender.
  • #### K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) showed a good performance with an accuracy of 96.84%.
  • #### Logistic Regression had the lowest accuracy at 79.53%, but it still provided a reasonable performance.

Overall, the Random Forest and Decision Tree models are the top performers, showing excellent accuracy in predictions. The Artificial Neural Network also proved to be very effective. The KNN model provided a good balance between simplicity and performance, while the Logistic Regression model, though slightly behind, still offers a solid baseline performance.¶
